24/07/2008
NEW YORK, United States -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ali Babacan stepped up his country's bid to secure a nonpermanent seat on the UN Security Council for 2009-2010 by holding a series of talks with UN envoys, Turkish media reported on Wednesday (July 23rd).
Late Tuesday, Babacan met representatives of more than 100 countries at a reception in New York, seeking their support.
He talked with the Latin American and Caribbean group, the Least Developed Countries and Srgjan Kerim, president of the 62nd session of the UN General Assembly.
He will also meet representatives of the African Union, the Arab League and the Organisation of the Islamic Conference.
Turkey is one of three candidates bidding for two seats allocated to the Western European and Others Group.
The other applicants are Iceland and Austria.
The election is scheduled for October.
(Zaman, Sabah, Turkish press - 23/07/08)
